body:
I have created a smaller reproducible example. Attached is a zip with a spec that reproduces the error which is now simplified to:

```
package bug/cmd/go-planting-server
	imports bug/restapi
	imports bug/restapi/operations
	imports bug/restapi/operations/v1
	imports bug/restapi/operations/v1: import cycle not allowed
```

To reproduce
```
$ tar -xvf bug.tar.gz
$ make run-server
```

Still using the same versions as above except for I upgraded `golang`:

```
matthew.hoggan in ~/Documents/go-planting
âš¡ go version
go version go1.19.3 darwin/amd64
```

[bug.tar.gz](https://github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/files/10169774/bug.tar.gz)

Running:

```
golangci-lint run --fix ./...
```

Unfortunately, does not fix the issue but does show better diagnostic output on where the issues are. All the fixes to cycles entailed removing unused import added by the code generator. Unfortunately, in the real code there are 121 endpoints and each has 3 files that need to be touched up, so manually modifying the files is not sustainable. Any suggestions on automated tooling to cleanup after the swagger generate server command?

In my Makefile I have added the following target.

```
  swagger-touchup:
    # We run find -- goimports twice because of cycles.
    find . -name "*.go" -exec goimports -w {} \; && \
      find . -name "*.go" -exec goimports -w {} \; && \
      find . -name "*.go" -exec gofmt -w {} \; && \
      find . -name "*.go" -exec gofmt -w {} \;
  .PHONY: swagger-touchup
```

This seems remove most of the cycles which are just unused imports anyways. Seems like to me we are just blindly adding imports. Unfortunately, server.go and main.go still have unused imports. It would be nice if go-swagger validated auto generated code and fixed issues before the program exited.

Updated `Makefile` now reads:

```
  swagger-touchup:
    # We run find -- goimports twice because of cycles.
    $(eval go_path := git.tcc.li/climate/pipelines/reg/go-planting/restapi)
    $(eval go_path := $(go_path)/operations)
    find . -name "*.go" -exec goimports -w {} \; && \
      find . -name "*.go" -exec goimports -w {} \; && \
      find . -name "*.go" -exec gofmt -w {} \; && \
      find . -name "*.go" -exec gofmt -w {} \; && \
      sed -i .bak '\|$(go_path)/v1|d' restapi/server.go && \
      sed -i .bak '\|$(go_path)/v3|d' restapi/server.go && \
      sed -i .bak '\|$(go_path)/v1|d' cmd/go-planting-server/main.go && \
      sed -i .bak '\|$(go_path)/v3|d' cmd/go-planting-server/main.go && \
      find . -name "*.bak" -exec rm {} \;
  .PHONY: swagger-touchup
```
This gets the server to build. Not going to close as done.

we do add a bunch of imports as hints and then expect goimports to clean them up.

I've confirmed that this behavior exists on my machine too. 
This is definitely not supposed to happen

Thank you @casualjim for the support. I will keep my eye on this thread for any updates. I am in the process of drafting a proposal for my employer (Bayer) on how to migrate existing `clojure` services over to `golang`. Services are deployed in docker containers using `debian`. However, local debugging and developing on our Macs is key. So generation of server and client code on our development machines will be a very important aspect of the migration. If I can be of any assistance please let me know.
Another observation one can make is that this only occurs for v1 and v3 endpoints. The legacy and v2 endpoints do not seem to exhibit this bug.

@mehoggan  it is a package mangling issue: the v[n] suffix has a special meaning for go imports and the codegen doesn't guard against that (yet). It is indeed a bug.

A quick fix is to alter the go naming of your tags like so:
```yaml
tags:
- name: core
  description: ''
- name: legacy nitro
  description: ''
- name: legacy umber
  description: ''
- name: v1
  description: ''
  x-go-name: version1
- name: v2-validations
  description: ''
- name: v3-validations
  description: ''
- name: v3
  description: ''
  x-go-name: version3
- name: v3-planned
  description: ''
- name: v3-actual
  description: ''
```

issue.title: fix(codegen): fixed operation package mangling when tag is v1
issue.body:
* fixes #2866

This PR addresses that case when tags used to generate a package to hold a group of operations are of the special form v[0-9]+.

This form is interpreted by go imports so that "x/v1" resolves as "x" in the program.

To fix the problem, "v[nnn]" package names are renamed "version[nnn]".
